top_comments: Alternative title: Bodybuilders discover calisthenics

Been doing deficit push ups with elevated feet for a few months now. Couple hints: 1) if using yoga blocks (like in the video, I recommend them) use your fists instead of the open hand. It will give you about 2 more inches for deficit movement, without having to strain your neck back . Also reduces the strain on your wrists since they are at a more severe angle than normal. With the foam yoga blocks, you won't hurt your knuckles. 2) If you do this at home, do it in front of the stairs. You can adjust the angle by changing which stair tread you use. 3) Use a weight vest for overloading. Once you do this for a while, you'll start blowing out the # of reps and will need to increase the load to keep seeing growth. You can use the vest for overloading a lot of other body weight exercises too, like squats.

When measured by weight (like in grams or ounces), fine sea salt and kosher salt have the same sodium content since they're both just sodium chloride (NaCl). The only difference comes when measuring by volume (like teaspoons) because kosher salt's larger flakes take up more space. 1 tsp of fine salt holds more crystals than 1 tsp of kosher salt, so you'd get more sodium that way. pDF_GUIeuo4.title: How I Built a MASSIVE 100kg Lifting Drone
top_comments: Bro, go to settings and click on initial tune parameters enter prop size and battery type, if you are using mission planner. I recommend mission planner. Reduce p , I , d (keep p and i equal)  of both roll and pitch till you get a stable hover in stabilize flight mode. Better use a telemetry radio instead of connecting a laptop to it every time. Reduce p and I in larger steps than D. All these value can be found in extended tuning tab of mission planner. Now once you get a stable hover , switch to althold with mot_thst_hover param set to 2. Disable it after a 30 second flight by changing the parameter to 0. Plug in the hover learn value into throttle to accel gains p= hover learn, I = 2*hover learn, then takeoff in althold and switch to loiter. If everything is fine, you can proceed with autotune. Don't use dampers for autopilot, it already has two IMUs damped internally. Square tubes (motor arms) can cause vibration because of pulse from the propeller,  passing over it , better use a round pipe or try notch filtering. Probably, you can't autotune it if the flight time is very less.

The reason that Makita doesn't seem as exciting as other tool brands comes down to their core culture as a high quality Japanese tool company.  They don't rush into anything, they don't jump on bandwagons, and they don't release anything until they think it is ready.  This doesn't mean that they don't make mistakes, or that they don't occasionally miss the mark; but it does mean that their build quality is top notch and when they do release a new tool, it is often a game changer in that tool class.  The flip side is that they release a new model every 7-10 years instead of every 2 years.  They take that time to study how the tool is used and how it breaks so that the next one is better.  I appreciate that they don't try to make the most powerful tool, they try to make the best tool for the job and job rating.  Sure, you can take a Milwaukee and push it till it screams and it will most often the most powerful version of that tool, but it will tear itself apart while doing that. A Makita will just shut off if you start asking it to do something it isn't intended to do.  On their impact wrenches people often complain that you can't slap a too big socket on it and blow it to bits, but the makita will just shut down and tell you "go get a bigger wrench that is meant for this bulldozer, I'm designed for a civic".

E0ZZ-uWKkwU.title: Mechanics React to Shop Pranks That Went Too Far
top_comments: Justin is a twin 😮
Justin has a twin and SANDRO HAS THE VAN!!!!

I worked as a CNA for a while, and me and one of my patients decided to play a prank on the dour old nurse on duty. The patient had a catheter, so I hid the bag on the back of the chair. I got a new catheter bag and filled it up with white grape juice, then strapped it to her leg (she was in on it, and wanted to do it) just like a normal catheter. When the nurse came in to assess her for the am meds, I pretended like I was emptying the catheter into a brand new measuring cylinder. After draining the very uriney-looking juice into the container, I stood there chatting up the nurse, and then casually just started taking sips...

She didn't notice the first one, but the second time her eyes went wide and she shrieked "what the hell are you doing?!!" By then, the patient was convulsing with silent laughter.

We also had a young guy who was paralyzed, but alert and responsive. I asked him if he wanted to play a prank on the oncoming night shift girl, and he nodded yes, and grinned. He was pretty big, so I usually had him in bed and squared away before she came on. That night, I pushed his chair into the bathroom like usual, but left him in it and threw a sheet over him, tucked just to the side so he was hidden, but could still see what was happening. I then went and laid down in his bed and covered myself with the sheet, and put my limbs in the position he was usually stuck in.

When she came in to check on him, she pulled the sheet back and I jumped out. She screamed so loud half of the administration came running down from the nurse's station to see what was wrong. The guy was in the corner laughing his head off and grinning from ear to ear. Lol.

In 2019, almost all of 2019 I was a Homeless Disabled Veteran. BUT, I had a roof over my head as I bounced around from Ohio State Park to Ohio State Park. I had food in my belly, with having my microwave in the trailer, my dorm fridge, my desk with my laptop and internet access. cUJ9NNMvduw.title: Its Beginning to Look Like Home. The Abandoned Tiny Home Project. Lot32 Destination Adventure.
top_comments: Hey brother, retired fire inspector here. You are very lucky that you didn't lose your home to fire. Oily stain type finishes and even cooking oil stained rags  have a known history of self ignition when balled up and packed in a bag or other combustible container. I remember a fire destroyed a million dollar home 2 or 3 weeks before the owners moved in. The flooring contractor was staining real wood floors and trim. His uninformed workers balled up the old stained rags and thew them in a corner. During the night they generated heat , ignited and burned the home down. A metal container for those with a tight lid can usually keep that from happening but I used to tell people to take that can outside and away from the house until they are ready for proper disposal. You can always get more rags pretty cheap. This spontaneous heating phenomenon through oxidation is very real.

As a mother of grown children. I was so worried when you stood on the frozen river. The "bold face lie" made me feel better. You rock Sir, but don't scare me like that again.😂😂😂 The emotional rollercoaster wheeewwww.💜

top_comments:
Long time listener. First time caller.
In our town 7-3/4 is max stair rise. You can also cheat the total rise down, creating a slight pitch to the treads for further savings on the total run.

I find 8" a bit tall for rise height personally.

Enjoying your content, thanks!

The only thing about the stairs you may not have (or maybe did?) take into account is if your stairs are not up to code (especially if intentional) and someone injures themselves on them, insurance may not cover you.  Since this is a rental/AirBnB, this could be a massive legal and financial liability. Especially since these videos are in the public domain and you have admitted on more than one occasion that you are only using the current stairs "to fool the code inspectors" or to "pass code".  Protect yourself, your family, and your future as a Youtuber, please.

In Europe we use something called the "stair formula". The rule is that "2x riser height plus 1x tread depth equals 65 cm / 26 inch" (which is the length of a human step). This means that you can make stairs as steep as you want, but when the riser height increases, the tread depth has to decrease accordingly. Applying this rule will result in comfortable stairs, no matter how lazy or steep.
The way you typically use this formula is that you take the distance from floor to floor, divide it by the number of steps (an integer value) which gives you the riser height. Then use the stair formula to determine the tread depth.
For example when the floor to floor height is 10 foot (120 inch) you can do 15 treads (the upper floor counts as one), resulting in a riser height of 8" and therefore a tread depth of 10". But for a steeper stair (maybe space is limited) you can decrease the number of treads to 12 where each step has a rise of 10" and a tread depth of 6". Both examples will work well, but the second one is getting close to a ladder. Of course when you need things like 11 or 13 steps, going metric and using a calculator makes this all much easier.
I've never seen this rule applied in North America. But especially outside sidewalks have often horrible stairs that make you stumble.

9cd09Y-hgyw.title: Bismarck’s Final Battle - The Bismarck Part 4
top_comments: Thanks for joining us on this naval adventure. Where should we set course for the next miniseries? Join the Timeghost Army to keep the wind in our sails!

My father was onboard HMS Dorsetshire during the Bismarck episode. He took part in the rescues of the 86 survivors picked up by Dorsetshire, before the rescue efforts had to be abandoned. One of the men he helped onboard, a member of turret "Dora's" gun house crew named Friedrich Junghans, gave dad his "erkennungsmarke" or dogtag in gratitude. Post war dad tried to return the dogtag to Friedrich but was unable to trace him. He later found out that Friedrich had died in Los Angeles USA in 1973, so in 1993 dad donated Friedrich's dogtag to the "Merseyside Maritime Museum" in Liverpool UK where it is still on display to this day.

The story of the Polish ship reminds of a friend I had long ago. I saw him on remembrance Sunday wearing his RAF gear and some medals, I recognised most but not one that was huge and shiny, he told me it was, "A coffee tin lid". I found out later where he got it. After spending time flying Lancasters he was swapped to teaching Poles how to fly, he said it was the scariest thing he ever did because they HATED the NAZI, (quite understandably I thought) and would fly at them no matter what. It was quite the statement considering he won the medal, which was Polish, for flying Polish spies into occupied Poland in a little Lysander aircraft. Thank you for reminding me of my friend.

As a dental professional of 25 years we see younger and younger kids asking about teeth bleaching when it really isn't necessary all because society says you have to have insanely white teeth that look like tic tacs. Can we normalise naturally white teeth which can have a very slightly yellowish hue, which is totally NORMAL? I talk more people out of bleaching to save their money than to promote it, the exposure to social media and people constantly seeing influencers and celebrities with bad veneers and crowns which are very unnatural and insanely white. I have had to pull out the shade guide and they are always surprised when I show them how white their teeth actually are.
Normal brushing/flossing and low staining foods with a hygiene appointment every 6 months is sufficient, imo. It does make me sad to hear young children asking about bleaching when they have naturally white teeth already, societal 'norms' are changing and there are a lot of dentist making money from people being insecure about their natural coloured teeth.

As a dental assistant, you're spot on! Another thing I would add to reduce sensitivity is not just brush with Sensodyne (or any equivalent with potassium nitrate) but after brushing, get a paper towel, dry your teeth, then rub some Sensodyne on them. Concentrate on the areas you're most sensitive - gum recession, etc. Leave it on for like 10 min then spit it out. We tell our patients to do this every day at least 2 weeks before starting any whitening treatment, as well as in between sessions.

u8N1YJHqskw.title: Why Young and Elderly People Experience Death Differently
top_comments:
My 17 year old grandson was in a roll over accident that left him as a quadriplegic. He only had control of his body from his head to his shoulders. But not down to his feet. He could move his arm but his fingers were gnarled. His brain functioned normally as he could speak and think. Some times I would sneak into his room at night and find him weeping. This broke my heart to see him looking out the window at other PPL doing what he should have been doing. We talked many a time about things.

He would say, " grandpa please get me some weed or even a bottle of crown to help ease my emotional pain . At first I would tell him that doesn't help. But after awhile I could not stand to see him suffer. The alcohol and weed helped him through a lot of pain I knew he was emotionally feeling.

I've been criticized for this on numerous occasions. But I felt his pain and gave him what he wanted. He passed 10 days before his 20th birthday. But he died peacefully after his spinal cord injury. I don't regret my actions. I was told he would die young by doctors. I know where his Spirit went as we talked about the after life and he gave his heart to the Lord. He has been relieved from his suffering which brings me peace. But I cry a lot as I miss him dearly. But the hope I have is that we will meet again at the resurrection. God rest his soul.

My 30 year old daughter just died from a brain stem injury 2 weeks ago. She was in hospice for 2 weeks. She never woke up. I watch your video's because you are very relatable and informative.  I appreciate you. Thank you

The biggest issue with Beeching was the attitude of BR (and the governments of the time) to the axed lines. It wasn't enough to just close the lines, they had to be destroyed immediately as well. It was as if they didn't want to permit the possibility that they could be proved wrong. Track was ripped up and scrapped, no one was allowed to buy lines to operate privately, land was sold for development. This was the greatest error. Deciding to close unprofitable lines was understandable given the way things looked at the time. Making sure they could never be reopened if the world changed was the true crime.

Beeching was commissioned to deliver exactly what the government of the day wanted all along, they wanted a reduction in active railways, and Beeching was the useful "scapegoat" to deflect attention away from the Government to get exactly that.

If not Beeching, the government would have simply found someone else happy to deliver what they wanted.

QKyEJeEAu50.title: THIS is the Spider Bite to Worry About - The Sydney Funnel Web
top_comments: What other venomous creatures should we investigate? Let me know in the replies!

As a kid in the seventies I lived in the outer suburbs of Newcastle 2 hours north of Sydney. We had an inground pool and I would check the bottom of the pool every morning. I would find two or three Funnel Webs every week. They looked dead until you scooped them out and placed them on the deck. After several minutes they would slowly come to life. I would place them in a jar and take them to a nearby ambulance station and they would then send them on to Sydney Wildlife Park where they were milked for their venom to produce antivenom. Caught hundreds over the years I was there.

Lived in Sydney all my life. in 1963 I was helping my dad in the garden and I was bitten by one that I accidentally walked on. 60 years later I can remember the pain on my ankle. By the time I got to hospital I could not feel below my waist. I was put in a coma and woke up 4 days later. No antivenom back then. I was in hospital for two weeks. The reported number of deaths is vastly under reported as stats have only been collected since about 1960. I admire your courage.  And now they have discovered the Big Boy Funnel Web. Its 50% bigger than the one you have there.

iK1ZZInYRHY.title: Amazon removes your right to download Kindle books
top_comments:
I had no intention of making two anti-Amazon videos in a row. I didn't even want to make another video about Amazon, as I'd like to focus on philosophical ideas and great books. But this news is time-sensitive, so I wanted to make a video right now to get the word out.

Look up Calibre and guides for removing DRM. Look for alternative ereaders. Buy physical media. Support local booksellers.

EDIT: There are some recurring questions in the comments. I can't address them all, but here are some thoughts.

Question: What is DRM?

DRM stands for Digital Rights Management. It is software that limits how you can use a digital asset. It the case of Kindles, DRM locks you into the Kindle ecosystem. It also helps to prevent piracy. This is the crux of the issue: in order to prevent piracy, companies restrict how you can use what you buy.

Question: Why not just pirate?

I want to support authors and artists.

Question: Does this affect your ability to read books on your Kindle or on a Kindle app?

No. This prevents you from downloading the files onto a folder on your computer, which you can currently do in order to save a local copy (or to use a program like Calibre to strip the DRM).

Question: Is it legal to remove DRM?

I am not a lawyer. I said in the video that to the best of my knowledge it was legal (thinking here only about using the content for personal use), but obviously the law is complex and varies by jurisdiction. You'll want to do your own research before taking any action.
If buying isn’t owning then pirating isn’t stealing.
My wife asked for a Kindle for Christmas, and I did some research on them and their competitors and how they manage  your purchases. Long story short: she's really been enjoying her Kobo.

I 100% agree with you that the "Doppler effect" explanation of sonic booms is misleading. top_comments: Inertal guidance with surfacing now and then for recalibration by GPS could be an option for the guidance system
never clicked faster in my life, go polish lads!

You could simply resurface periodically to get GPS position and use that position as a starting point with water velocity and compass bearing (magnetic field is not impeded by water) for relative motion. Obviously sea currents are a thing, so while surfaced, turn off propulsion and measure the velocity to get a sea current vector. Use this measurement to offset derived location.

For turning you should use rudders not fins, ie. place them after the propeller. That way you get a sort of thrust vectoring.

Will be on the lookout for stuff like this, great video as always Dave.
My favorite thing about your video's: as knowledgeable as you are, youre not ashamed or afraid to ask for help when you run into new problems. Never letting your ego get in the way like many would

As a tech, we tend to teardown to point of failure - nothing further. Anything further is wasted time and $$ being flatrate. Most of the time, we’re ripping the pan off anyways to get the crank unseized, and that’s far enough for us and GM. Great find and thank you for doing these though, as they’re insightful. I’ve done at least 20 of these L87s, and a handful of LT1/LT4s for this failure. I’ve had a few L82/L84 with rod issues and ringland issues with <20k too. Quality left out of seemingly nowhere.

Z_gV1hEqlA8.title: Can you "see" images in your mind? Some people can't - Adam Zeman
top_comments: I heard "Count sheeps in your head if you can't fall asleep" when I was young. I thought it was like a saying, but never actually realised that people CAN see sheep in their heads. Years later, I found out it was called aphantasia.
As someone with hyperphantasia, I would say it's both a bless and a curse, I can relive the good times in my mind, but the traumas are equally vivid and unforgettable.

I don’t see any images in my head. (except when I’m dreaming). I didn’t realize other people actually saw things in their mind until a couple years ago and that was so hard to wrap my head around. For me, while I’m not visualizing things, I can still conceptualize a thing or a scene. Like, if a book described a character and female, white, brunette with long hair and high cheekbones, I have seen women who look like that and can conceptualize what that character might look like. but there’s no mental imagine to accompany it.

During the covid shutdown, my wife and I drove from Oregon over to Long beach in Washington state. Most places were closed but this one woman was running a fish & chips place off the main drag. It took forever to get our food because she was working alone. I was getting a little salty because the food was taking a while. When she called us to get our food, she included 2 little flag pins in the bag.

Those little pins really touched me, and I immediately realized how wrong and awful my outlook was. How much this woman had invested in herself and helping this small community and how strong her spirit and support of the country was. That was probably 4 years ago, and I still rock that flag pen on one of my hats.

top_comments:
A complete or partial break in a bone.
A bone fracture is a complete or partial break in a bone. Causes include trauma, overuse and diseases that weaken bones.
Symptoms include a limb or joint that looks out of shape, or a bone that has poked through the skin. If the broken bone is an arm or a leg, the toe or finger may become numb or change color at the tip.
Treatment often involves resetting the bone in place and putting it in a cast to allow it time to heal. Sometimes, surgery or metal rods may be needed to reset the bone. A broken bone usually heals in 4 to 8 weeks, but healing time can vary widely. Healing depends on many factors, including the type of bone, the severity of the break, and the person's age and health.
Factors that affect healing time
Bone type: Smaller bones heal faster than larger bones.
Break severity: The more severe the break, the longer it will take to heal.
Age: Children heal faster than older adults.
Health: Underlying health conditions like diabetes or osteoporosis can slow healing.
Lifestyle: Smoking, poor nutrition, and lack of exercise can slow healing.
Healing phases
Healing occurs in three phases:
Inflammatory phase: Bleeding and cell death occur at the fracture site.
Repair phase: New bone, cartilage, and fibrous tissue form at the fracture site.
Remodeling phase: The fracture callus is replaced with new bone over many months.

It feels inherently commercial to me to want to take the work out of its context, like they want to be able to trade on the famous title and pretend it has less objectionable content than it does, rather than promoting any lesser-known works with actually better politics as alternatives.

MRoxo0n2YN8.title: Inside a totally grilled factory high bay LED bulb
top_comments: Like a lot of things, Everything dies to protect the fuse. 😂

I remember many moons ago I worked for a large US retail brand and in the warehouse we had the top half of one of those rubber orange traffic cones. I didn't know what it was used for until one day the warehouse supervisor went out with the lift to replace a failed metal falide bulb with that same massive socket as your thing there. They'd use the parking cone to grip the bulb, still too hot to touch, and unscrew it. Worked out pretty well! I always wonder what the engineers who designed these must think when they see someone with a traffic cone changing their bulb?

Engineered to work in a clean room.
Applied in industrial or greenhouse conditions they never lasted long.

kHphBGcR6Ps.title: Steel Cable Damascus
top_comments: Big thank you to our sponsor: Go to https://ground.news/alec to stay fully informed and access reliable information. Save 40% on the Ground News unlimited access Vantage plan with my link.
I love that Alec can name a video "Steel Cable Damascus" and we all just think "say no more"

Hey Alec, as a professional metallurgist working in a heat treat plant, your varying hardness results are coming from your quench. High carbon steels generate a case when oil quenched, caused by the transformation of the austenite to martensite crystal structures as it cools down. This transformation needs to happen extremely quickly, on the order of 0.5-5 seconds depending on the alloy, otherwise the carbon has time to move around too much and find where it wants to be. This means that you generally only get high hardness right on the surface, as the core cant cool fast enough to transform into martensite. This case is usually only 0.010-0.060" deep, the rest of the core will be much lower.
Inconsistant agitation or slowly lowering the piece into the oil will also lead to differing hardnesses across the part, because the part heats up the oil surrounding it which reduces the oils ability to remove the heat from the steel. The more oil you have in your container, the better, and most professional quench tanks have internal impellers or recirculation to make sure that the oil right next to the part is always being replaced by cooler new oil.
Awesome job as always, excited to see more!

DEGJgQjdfyo.title: Wow, my Vit D is low
top_comments: How is the NHS ever going to function properly when there is a conflict between pharma profits and public health?

This is a very interesting point. I work in hospital labs and we require a reason to request vitamin d level test. Taking into consideration that we are in a country with low sunshine exposure you would think that there would be an emphasis on testing.

Hi Dr Campbell, I have followed your channel since 2020 and always find your videos informative and interesting. I am a retired NHS Biomedical scientist and have performed Vitamin D analysis in the past. It used to be a very expensive test, so was rationed to those patients in the highest need. However, since I retired, I believe the testing of Vit D has moved to a more automated methodology and may be cheaper to do. It may still be worth a chat to your GP to see if they are willing to do it at your local hospital. With respect, the test that you were using on your video, would not be acceptable in a medical laboratory, NHS or Private, (at least, not in my day!) These home testing kits can be hit and miss in my experience. If I may offer a suggestion, it would be to get a blood test done by an accredited laboratory, even if you have to have one privately, before you up the Vit D dosage, then you could confirm the test kit was accurate or not, it would also confirm that you are taking the correct amount of Vit D or not. If you up your dose and then use a different kit you still won't know which one made the difference. I take 6000iu a day of D with a meal containing fat or a glass of whole milk to improve absorption. I haven't had my levels checked but I seem to be avoiding all the respiratory illnesses that are afflicting my friends and family, so, fingers crossed. Thanks for all the work you do - you are one of the good guys.

Before you go tearing your car apart thinking you have this problem, check the plastic clip in the trunk that holds the tension rods (not really sure what you call them) in the rear deck.  I had a 2015 Camry XSE with a sunroof and whenever the body flexed and twisted like Amd described, there was a very loud pop/bang that was difficult to localize where it was coming from.  Sometimes it sounded like it was coming from the sunroof, other times the right rear suspension.  The sound is solid and travels through the entire body of the car.  I fought it for weeks by myself, then finally had my father-in-law drive the car while I sat in different areas to try and find the source.  I ended up riding in the trunk and found it.  A small, stupid plastic clip under the rear deck was allowing those metal rods to flex and pop.  Check that first as it's much easier and cheaper to fix.  Toyota part# 64127-06110 for years 2015-2018.

wxSwYUennBA.title: Exercise Actually Makes Chronic Fatigue Syndrome Worse
top_comments: this is what people with cfs have been saying for years

I was ultra fit before I got sick. I was a gym manager, PT, climbed mountains (old videos still on my channel 😢), loved body building, cycling… I lived to be active. I fought with every ounce of my being to keep going when I first got sick. This ensured I became permanently worse and worse. Almost 8 years later, I am 100% housebound, horizontal, use a wheelchair when I rarely go outside (to medical appointments only). I’ve lost my entire life. And people STILL think we’re just not trying hard enough…. Apparently we just can’t be bothered to get better…..

One thing worth highlighting is that a PEM crash can permanently lower your baseline. For example, maybe you can manage a walk around the block once a week, but one day you over-extend and crash, and now the maximum you can manage is getting from the bedroom to the kitchen, and any more than that is enough to trigger the next crash.

Edit: I'm not a doctor and can't advise anyone to do anything other than read up-to-date research and see someone who is a doctor.

Two weeks before the race, I ceased running, hoping to recover by race day on December 1st. I didn’t seek a diagnosis or imaging because I didn’t want to believe it was a fracture that would prevent me from racing.

On race day, I chose to compete and aimed for a sub-3-hour finish in my first marathon. Ibuprofen and adrenaline masked the pain. At 30 km, I was still on pace but realized I had caused significant damage. I finished in 3 hours flat, later discovering I had sustained a grade 4 fracture in my leg.

After the race, my leg was incredibly swollen, and I couldn’t walk properly for a few weeks. Following this, I stopped running. It’s been 10 weeks with no pain at rest or while walking. I decided to get an MRI to establish a comeback plan, which confirmed a grade 4 (severe) fracture.

And now we’re here.

Time to create a build-back plan.

Moral of the story:

Do not run through pain. It’s not tough; it’s stupid.

I appreciate the determination and grit etc. I'm an ultra runner as well. But man, Nick sets an unrealistic view of what training really looks like. The dude’s volume when factoring in lifting etc and never taking any real time off is insane. I'm glad he's going to recover but you don't need to go this far before having that realization. I wish him the best. Listen to your body peeps.

y_ygTVwu9aM.title: This Isn’t a 1440p GPU Anymore… 🥲
top_comments: To make it clear one more time, I LOVE the RX 6700 XT. It’s some of the best value you can find on the used market right now. But if you want to play new, graphically demanding games in 1440p, there are better options.
“Great question bud” 💀

For those unfamiliar with the nomenclature: Most techies rate a GPU based upon their performance with current (within the past year) AAA releases. Keep in mind that devs recently have a predilection towards "graphical showcases" - purely aesthetic visuals which tend to be quite demanding for GPUs.

To label a GPU as 1440p is to assure potential buyers that they can reliably play these titles at High (vs Ultra, Medium, or Low) and get an appropriate frame rate (varies by title; higher for twitch/FPS, etc).

Older titles are (generally) less-demanding graphically, and one can anticipate every 3-5 years of age to bump the playability for that title. A 1080p GPU can deliver solid 1080p performance with a newer title like Black Ops 6, but can also reliably deliver 1440p performance with an older title like Overwatch or Modern Warfare. (And potentially handle an even older title like Minecraft in 4K.)

He also mentioned other early Swedish systems that were important at the time like the Cencor 908, developed by Stansab in Järfälla, which was used very early on for building airport traffic management systems. The Cencor 908 was especially interesting since it ended up causing an international incident in the early 1970s when Stansab sold one of the aforementioned traffic management systems to the Moscow airport. This was problematic not only because we had given a system that could easily be repurposed for military use to the USSR but also because there were bans on exporting many of the advanced and sensitive American made components in the Cencor 908 to the USSR. A: Right now we’re not planning to. If a reputable manufacturer reaches out to us and wants to work with us to sell some, we might be open to it.

Q: What about selling kits?
A: With the current hardware, kits would be pricey and we’re not sure how much demand there would be. Maybe if the design is improved (see notes below) and the hardware cost can be reduced, someone from our community might be able to sell kits, but the two of us will likely not so we can keep making videos.

Thoughts on potential improvements:

*Price reduction opportunities: 1) Cheaper monitor mounts that would be compatible (might require small design tweak). 2) If the tablet holders could be replaced by something that can be 3D printed. 3) Once the design has been improved by the community, someone selling a kit can bring prices down by buying in bulk.

Height adjustment: It would be great if the height adjustment locked. This feature might be hard to implement though since it would make height adjustment more troublesome than friction based selfie sticks.

Base: A better design might be to have just a flat platform base with room for various keyboards and some sort of keyboard lock. The easy and inelegant solution would just be to hot glue a keyboard of choice down haha. Another solution would be for the community to develop a few different bases for a few popular keyboard options.

“Mini” version: I wonder if anyone would be interested in making a “mini” version for Android tablets or iPads that are as small as possible while still keeping a full size keyboard and the adjustable height capabilities.

Framework laptop version. I think it would be really cool if instead of making the top able to switch between tablets, we went with a replaceable component strategy instead and used Framework laptop components to make an easy to repair ergonomic laptop.

Big stretch goal: make it compatible with “normal laptops”. This might mean some sort of shelf to set a laptop on where the laptop can be secured down in some way or some sort of other clever solution. Hopefully this could just be a swap for the top bar, keeping the base and arms the same.

Finalize the name! Some potential contenders are ErgoTop, Ergonomic Laptop Frame (E.L.F.), ErgoTablet, ErgoStand, ErgoFrame, ErgoRig, OrthoTop, LiftTop…

bq4su2Lp2iw.title: The Experiment That Proved Atoms Are Mostly Empty Space
top_comments: I can't tell you how exciting it was for me to recreate this experiment that I had learned about since I was in high school! Such an iconic experiment!

The way Ernest Rutherford and his team did that experiment has a lot more interesting details, they didn't have the fancy equipment like the Geiger counter that we have today, rather they had to depend on fluorescent screen coated with zinc sulfide, when alpha particles hit this screen they produce a small flash of light which isn't really visible to the eye.

The screen was circularly wrapped around the gold foil to allow for detection from all different directions (except the small path to make the alpha particles pass through and hit the gold foil)
but these flashes are super tiny, so they had to be a completely dark room, but before they can even begin the experiment they would sit in the darkened laboratory for hours, to make their eyes dark adapted enough, to make them more sensitive to very dim lights, on top of that each observer in the dark room would have a carefully positioned microscope aimed specific portion of the screen to able to see these flashes, as they had to be magnified to be visible to the human eye, they would do this day after day spending hours in this dark room manually counting flashes

If it's all just empty space beyond the nucleus, what determines the outer bound of the atom? Is the emptiness around the nucleus just the electron orbital? What forces keep the electron "bound" to the nucleus?

I'm 11 and don't know the correct terms to formulate a coherent set of questions, so I hope someone can illuminate me on the subject. I apologize if I used incorrect terminology. Please correct me if I did.

bAP06HIoR78.title: Fixing wood dents
top_comments:
The wood is compressed in a dent. When you sanded it the first time, you removed material from around the dent, but not in the dent. When you expanded the wood, the conpressed wood in the dent expanded to its original shape, bulging out to the same height as presanding.
Had you not sanded the wood initially, there would be no bulge.

The science is pretty simple, heat increases flexibility of the fibers, and the water evaporates and pushes the dented wood out with it.
Saw the other video yesterday and the final product looked amazing!

Forcing moisture back in the pores. When wood gets "dented", it releases the moisture. Well, thats what my woodworking teacher taught us 25 years ago.
Think about it😂

26:00 I'm a Jeweler! For the best / most efficient use of a jewelry saw, always make sure the blade is considerably tight; you should be able to pluck it like a guitar string and hear a high pitched "ping" noise. Second, the use of a little BurLife or even beeswax goes a long way, but try not to over-do this because after excessive amounts, it wont bite into the workpiece at all. Probably the most important tip is to try keeping the orientation of the saw as vertical as possible, and only apply pressure to the workpiece on downward strokes. (im sure you know already but the saw blades are directional) Finally, maintaining a consistant cutting speed is more important than you might think. As im sure you've noticed, jewelry saw blades are extremely fragile, so with an inconsistent speed you run the risk of the blade banging around or catching when you dont expect it to, causing breaks. This is especially true when cutting thicker material, like in your application. I hope this helps, love your videos!

I love listening to you talk about specific forging requirements, traditions, styles, etc. Your videos feel like they lean slightly more towards educational/narrative, rather than something deliberately dramatized. I really appreciate that.

zavQRGSENlk.title: This Crop is WAY Better Than Potatoes (And No One Grows It!)
top_comments:
We live on Vancouver Island,
& I planted five tubers in March of 2015.
I’ve never planted them again,
& I get a bountiful harvest every year!
I don’t know the verities, some are yellow,
& some are orange red.
Unfortunately, they have pretty much taken over,
a 3.5m X 2M raised garden bed.
I won’t do that again, but since they’re there, we’ll eat them!
Garden carefully folks, smile often!

For those worried about spreading; I highly recommend the variety 'Supernova' since the tubers form within a foot from the base. Whereas other varieties can form three or more feet away. Supernova is on the shorter side at around 7 feet compared to as much as 14 or more feet for particularly tall varieties.

For those seeking the highest yield I recommend 'Stampede'. It is an interesting variety in that it is day neutral for tuber and flower production; meaning that it flowers and sets tubers only based on maturity and doesn't need shortening days to trigger like most varieties.

For those seeking a truly dwarf variety; I recommend 'Red Dwarf' which only gets 18 inches tall. It also produces tubers directly on the stem so it won't spread at all.

There are other non-spreading varieties that I am trialing but I don't want to claim anything until I'm sure.

Grow sunchokes!

Big fan of the channel just wanted to make a comment to make sure people are safe when fermenting. As someone that has a restaurant that specializes in fermentation I have fermented well just about everything. Tubers and alliums are just about the most dangerous thing to ferment so id take some precautions when doing sun chokes and alliums. It can be done don't get me wrong and it's a great idea and way to preserve but id suggest two things. The safest salinity to begin with is 2% of weight. So don't just season it and guess. Weigh the product including the water on a gram scale and add 2% salt and shake it up to dissolve. Anything below 2% leaves the door open to bad things especially with tubers and alliums. Secondly add a tablespoon of vinegar to start off with an acidic environment when doing tubers and alliums. This will keep the window open for better lactic acid development and shorten the window for the bad. Happy safe fermenting folks!

7er194F4erE.title: My Wind Generator Was Useless....Until NOW! (MPPT)
top_comments: Why did you cover your power supply's logo?
You realize we are all now fully invested into this series, right? Cant wait to see what you come up with for that Buck/Boost IC you picked up! 🎉

What's fascinating is that nearly every brand of "solar generator" (Anker, Ecoflow, Bluetti...) has implemented a well optimized, high efficiency buck/boost MPPT controller on their units. These controllers often have very sophisticated self-monitoring, and automatically adjust for a wide range of DC sources. So convenient!

As a solar/battery system builder myself, I find it incredibly infuriating that standalone modules with this tech do not exist, or at least are very rare and obscure. A buck/boost MPPT controller with fast active tracking would be an absolute game-changer for 48V systems, especially portable systems that benefit from versatility. This tech has already proven massively beneficial on the solar generator market, so why hasn't someone come along to fill the gap in the DIY market??

Re-ringing is not some 2 hour job guys. Head has to come off. Lower end off. Crank out.
Are we reusing to old 150k mile timing chains? Rod bearings? Main bearings?
Head gasket set, head bolts, rings, and the many hours of labor.
Same price as replacing with a used engine. ZERO savings.

Toyota tech here. As a long shot. Take the plugs out. Fill cylinders with seafoam or Gm top end clean. Let sit for 30 minutes. Suck it out turn it over by hand a few times. Then crank it for a few minutes.

As long as the rings are just carbon stuck and not blown out I have had this bring 6-7 of these back from the dead. Def not a fix. But it bought the customer time with a working vehicle

hFMaT9oRbs4.title: How to measure the universe | The Cosmic Distance Ladder Part 2
top_comments:
Terry kindly put together an FAQ with added details and corrections about what we discussed in the interview: https://terrytao.wordpress.com/2025/02/13/cosmic-distance-ladder-video-with-grant-sanderson-3blue1brown-commentary-and-corrections/

I'll pull out a few notable ones for inclusion here:

18:08 Can we really measure the entire Milky Way with this method?

Strictly speaking, there is a “zone of avoidance” on the far side of the Milky Way that is very difficult to measure in the visible portion of the spectrum, due to the large amount of intervening stars, dust, and even a supermassive black hole in the galactic center. However, in recent years it has become possible to explore this zone as well using the radio, infrared, and x-ray portions of the spectrum.

20:26 Was Hubble the one to discover the redshift of galaxies?

This was an error on my part; Hubble was using earlier work of Vesto Slipher on these redshifts, and combining it with his own measurements of distances using the Cepheid technique to arrive at the law that now bears his name. It should also be noted that Georges Lemaître had also independently arrived at essentially the same law a few years prior, but his work was published in a somewhat obscure journal and did not receive broad recognition until somewhat later.

20:46 Does general relativity alone predict a uniformly expanding universe?

This was an oversimplification. Einstein’s equations of general relativity contain a parameter \Lambda, known as the cosmological constant, which currently is only computable from experimental data. But even with this constant fixed, there are multiple solutions to these equations (basically because there are multiple possible initial conditions for the universe). For the purposes of cosmology, a particularly successful family of solutions are the solutions given by the Lambda-CDM model. This family of solutions contains additional parameters, such as the density of dark matter in the universe. Depending on the precise values of these parameters, the universe could be expanding or contracting, with the rate of expansion or contraction either increasing, decreasing, or staying roughly constant. But if one fits this model to all available data (including not just red shift measurements, but also measurements on the cosmic microwave background radiation and the spatial distribution of galaxies), one deduces a version of Hubble’s law which is nearly linear, but with an additional correction at very large scales; see the next item of this FAQ.

21:07 Is Hubble’s original law sufficiently accurate to allow for good measurements of distances at the scale of the observable universe?

Not really; as mentioned in the end of the video, there were additional efforts to cross-check and calibrate Hubble’s law at intermediate scales between the range of Cepheid methods (about 100 million light years) and observable universe scales (about 100 billion light years) by using further “standard candles” than Cepheids, most notably Type Ia supernovae (which are bright enough and predictable enough to be usable out to about 10 billion light years), the Tully-Fisher relation between the luminosity of a galaxy and its rotational speed, and gamma ray bursts. It turns out that due to the accelerating nature of the universe’s expansion, Hubble’s law is not completely linear at these large scales; this important correction cannot be discerned purely from Cepheid data, but also requires the other standard candles, as well as fitting that data (as well as other observational data, such as the cosmic microwave background radiation) to the cosmological models provided by general relativity (with the best fitting models to date being some version of the Lambda-CDM model).

21:15 Where did this guess of the observable universe being about 20% of the full universe come from?

There are some ways to get a lower bound on the size of the entire universe that go beyond the edge of the observable universe. One is through analysis of the cosmic microwave background radiation (CMBR), that has been carefully mapped out by several satellite observatories, most notably WMAP and Planck. Roughly speaking, a universe that was less than twice the size of the observable universe would create certain periodicities in the CMBR data; such periodicities are not observed, so this provides a lower bound (see for instance this paper for an example of such a calculation). The 20% number was a guess based on my vague recollection of these works, but there is no consensus currently on what the ratio truly is; there are some proposals that the entire universe is in fact several orders of magnitude larger than the observable one.

So I want to add that Leavitt didn't just measure the Cepheids, she discovered this behavior in the first place and built the catalogue of these stars - and her work with Ejnar Hertzsprung was what showed that the Greater Magellanic Cloud was much farther away than anything else, a good 50kpc. That didn't just measure the first distance to another galaxy - it showed that galaxies existed in the first place, something that was neither obvious nor expected before then!

Z1XeOppqUGQ.title: Inside a $5 AliExpress WiFi repeater
top_comments:
The data lines being connected isn't really anything that suspicious. That is almost certainly to allow downloading firmware updates via the USB connection, which is a very common function with these sorts of devices (and I believe built into most Mediatek chips by default).

The two antennas are almost certainly not separated into "receive" and "transmit". Both antennas are used for both functions. The use of two (or more) antennas allows for MIMO triangulation and multipath propagation to increase the accuracy and distance of the RF communication (essentially, it can use the phase difference between the signal on the two antennas to distinguish between signals coming from different physical locations, or to boost the signal strength in a particular direction when communicating with clients in that direction, etc).

Frankly, if you are worried about what code might be inside something like this, then you probably shouldn't be sending all your network traffic through it, or giving it access to your internal WiFi network anyway. Blindly trusting it with your WiFi data and passwords, but being afraid of the USB port is kinda a missing-the-forest-for-the-trees sort of thing, IMHO.
You should dump the flash chip for science. Lots of folks here would like to poke around

top_comments:
I would love to read your thoughts on this and discuss! 🚨 Some actionable steps to take:
- download your kindle ebooks to your computer (there are many videos on how to do this, but here’s one from CriminOlly: https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=KMoCzeGnIss )
- if you don’t own a kindle but have purchased kindle ebooks to read using their app, I have found a way to download them even if the option is greyed out on Amazon (link to Reddit thread with instructions is in the description box)
- shop from other ebook providers, especially those without DRM (TOR.com is a great option!)
- buy physical media for the things you really don’t want to lose
- support your local library!!!
- reach out to your local representative to express dismay at the lack of protections for consumers AND the increasing book bans, if that applies to you where you live
I stoped buying strictly digital content the first time a movie I purchased wasn’t available because amazon temporarily lost the rights. Anything I want to “own” I buy in hard copy.

NTw7KePgPTA.title: Pipe thread is designed to leak || AvE hydraulic
top_comments: I have to tell you my favorite fitting story. I designed and built chemical plants that made high end stuff for the pill makers. They were PhD MDs and what not.  Our reptilian salesman comes to me and ask me to set up our trucks with a rare set of fittings and to provide the mating fittings to the customers (the PhDs). I asked why. He said it was so that only our tank truck would flange up to their plant and we would get 100% of the business and nudge our competitor out. I said no way the customer is that stupid. Salesman explains that the design of the system is also signed off and approved by the govt. FDA guys and that the customer will never alter the plant in order to please the FDA.  You get all this? The slimy sales guy want's bastardo fittings to obtain a monopoly with the customer. These guys had more degrees than a thermometer but couldn't see through the scam. You know what - It worked. The PhDs told the competitor that their equipment would not interface with customers El Bastardo fittings. Chaching.  What fittings you ask? It was 1-1/4" thingamajig based on a British thread. I had it adapted to the class 150 2" ASME flange on the truck and the mirror image on the customer side.
Npt are great at sealing, and sturdy. I have seen 40 year old boiler systems where hundreds of fittings still don't leak.

Although, the fireplace looks very nice, some point on when projects with releasing energy (especially heat) are concerned. It would have been beneficial to think not only about how it looks and the amazing feeling it provides, to the people around, when burning, but also some way to store, some part of all that released (heat) energy. The fire that you are showing, based on simple estimation released around  500-1000 KWh (electrical equivalent) heat. That heat is enough to provide household water for almost 9-12 months, or heat the house for 3-4 weeks. Capturing even (only) 20% of that heat in a (well insulated) hot water thermal storage will provide quite a good source of heat energy not to speak that working on such a project will provide you also with a glimpse of how one can be as much as possible heat energy independent, if that is of a bigger interest of course.

rqfNFb-fD7Y.title: How Many Times a Day Should You Eat Protein?
top_comments: I started the 1g pre body weight about 5 months ago.  I have been able to increase training time and strength.  Also noticed my recovery time is about a day.  Also 5g creatine a day

Here's the break down / too long didn't watch :

Old studies were flawed – They tested protein intake on small, untrained individuals, so the "30g max" claim is outdated.
Daily protein target – About 1g per pound of body weight, with at least 75% from quality sources (meat, soy, etc.).
Eating all protein in one meal is bad – Your body burns extra protein for energy instead of muscle growth, leaving you with nothing for later.
Too many small meals is also bad – Eating tiny amounts all day is inefficient, like stopping for gas every 45 minutes on a road trip.
4-5 protein meals per day is ideal – Keeps a steady muscle-building process without being annoying.
Each meal should have equal protein – Take your daily protein goal and divide by 4 or 5.
More than 30g per meal is fine – Especially if you’re bigger and train hard. Whole food protein digests slower, so a 70g steak meal works great over time.

top_comments: Michelle posting 2 vlogs in 1 week is best thing ever

Michelle if you love eating rice and it’s your daily food item and are concerned about the glucose spikes after eating rice then decrease the starch or the carbohydrate content of rice. It’s the starch/carbohydrate of rice that results in the glucose spikes which is a normal physiologic response for everyone after eating.
An endocrinologist once recommended decreasing the starch content of rice by pouring off the starchy white water of rice during its cooking when it boils. To do this do not use a rice cooker but cook the rice in a pot the old fashion way. As the rice boils and the water turns white, pour off the starchy white water and add new water to the rice and continue cooking.
I would also add that another way to decrease the starch/carbohydrate from rice is to wash the rice extra times or soak the rice in water overnight thus removing starch/carbohydrate from the rice and discarding the water from the overnight soaked rice. Add new water before cooking the rice. This changes and lessens the chewy texture of rice that you love. The texture is a drier cooked rice and closer to the Chinese type of rice.
As long as you are not a diabetic, eating rice using your current cooking method and eating it in moderacy is acceptable.
Whenever you eat anything, especially rice and similar carbohydrate-rich foods, there’s a spike in the “sugar” level which is a normal response and your body’s own insulin resolves those spikes and normalizes the glucose level.

Not sure if it helps or you might already know this - eating soup or veggies first will help not spike your insulin levels even if you have rice!! I think the general order is soup - veggies - meat - rice! I love rice too so I hope this helps😊

I was a technical engineer with the former International Laser Systems, and they were requested to help another company that had built a Schlieren system .  .  . but couldn’t make it work.  I was sent to help and found they had a similar size mirror to yours but it was an off axis parabolic and used a laser source.  This uses similar principles to setting up to yours but has additional mirror constraints and requires critical alignment to achieve optimal focus.  I had never aligned a Schlieren before but understanding the principles of the system I quickly stepped through the alignments to get the system operational.  Now your setup has me thinking.  I have a 5” spherical mirror that I can work with to build one similar to yours for myself.  Seeing the tiny changes in the air’s index of refraction is a super power for analyzing many things and fun as well.  Thanks for the video!

Description:
Phoenix, Arizona — On February 12, 2025, Officers from the Cactus Park Precinct were conducting a follow up investigation regarding a drug related arrest from the week prior. This follow up led officers to the area of 27th Avenue and Northern where they attempted to contact two men in a white SUV who were believed to be conducting drug sales. The officers surrounded the SUV with marked patrol vehicles both behind and in front. After the officers were in position, they got out of their patrol cars and gave the two men commands to get out of their car. Both men remained in the car and the driver began to drive away from the officers. When they pulled away, they struck two marked patrol vehicles and drove in the direction of an officer. Two officers fired their handguns in the direction of the SUV. The SUV continued to drive away from the officers and drive west on Northern Avenue. Officers lost sight of the SUV for a short time, but ultimately located it again and a pursuit was initiated as the SUV continued to take off at a high rate of speed.

This pursuit continued to the area of 59th Avenue and Northern where the passenger of the SUV got out of the car and ran into a nearby apartment complex. The driver of the SUV took off from officers until it lost control and was involved in a collision. Officers then arrested the driver of the SUV. Officers converged on the apartment complex where the passenger was last seen. During their search, officers located the passenger. A less lethal 37mm launcher was used to gain full compliance from the man. A 37mm launcher fires a less-lethal direct impact baton which is designed to deliver pain compliance. This tool is only used by members of the Tactical Support Bureau. After both men were arrested, each was found to have non-fatal gunshot wounds. Both were transported to a nearby hospitals for treatment. Both have been released from medical care and booked into jail on multiple charges stemming from the incident. During a search of the SUV, officers located several types and quantities of illicit drugs.

al7_0j1h9x4.title: The Greatest Brownie Recipe of All Time (The GOAT)
top_comments: We finally did it but I still want to know your thoughts. If you make this one, PLEASE let me know what you think. Is it The GOAT? Get 40% off your first Hungryroot box PLUS get a free item of your choice in every box for life with code BRIAN at https://bit.ly/40eFl0J
Man, I’ve been waiting for this for a week😅

Chemist here. As I understand it, proteins and sugars get pushed to the surface by the water (which converts to steam) and air bubbles (which expand) inside the brownie batter as it bakes. Once it reaches the surface, proteins begin to harden and trap the air bubbles. Simultaneously, sugars begin to crystallize and then caramelize. This results in the thin, shiny skin we see on top of the brownie. In order for the sugars to crystallize, there needs to be nucleation sites present for the crystals to grow. But if there’s plenty of sugar in the batter relative to water content, then this shouldn’t cause an issue. But this ratio cannot be too high. Otherwise, there’s not enough water to push the sugars and proteins up.

My guess is that using a utensil can disperse the nucleation sites unevenly, leading to uneven skin development and cracking.

Adam Ragusea posted a pretty lengthy video on brownie skin specifically, and he doesn’t seem to be having any issues with skin forming even when using a rubber spatula. So I don’t think it hinders the skin development so much as it can lead to cracking and blotchy patches of brownie skin.

Hope this helps!

JCvLbT1uXXg.title: We Will Eradicate Measles
top_comments: Hank. I'm in the kitchen, watching this, on a low-ish volume. I hear my 5yo's voice from the living room, "Are you watching SciShow?!"

I was one of those kids who could not be vaccinated for a period as a child due to a medical condition (if you're severely immunocompromised there are some types of vaccines you can't get). I recovered and was then able to catch up on all my vaccines and I am SO GRATEFUL to the millions of people who unknowingly contributed to my ability to survive by being part of the herd immunity against measles and several other illnesses. I take my responsibility now as a part of that herd immunity for kids coming behind me so seriously.

One extra terrifying thing about measles: it wipes out your immunity for other diseases. With measles immune amnesia, your immune system forgets how to fight the things that it has already overcome, leaving you vulnerable to all kinds of other diseases. And this immune amnesia lasts 2-5 YEARS. Studies looking at child mortality rates before and after the measles vaccine was introduced concluded that up to half of all childhood deaths could be linked to the measles immune amnesia - meaning that kids who survived measles still died of its effects when another infectious disease came along.

The only way to prevent measles immune amnesia? Get vaccinated and don't get measles. That's literally all we can do. And it's pretty cool that a vaccine for one disease can help prevent you dying from other ones!

couple tips for anyone who wants them, clamp the replacement panel in place over the old material and cut through them both at the same time with an angle grinder thin disk but have the blade at a 45 degree angle, itll create a tight fit up, if you cut them both with the grinder at 90 degrees to the panel you get a blade width gap

when welding the seams dont aim for the seam immediately, put the puddle onto you thicker piece and then drag it upward.. if its really thin sometimes you have to run a whole bead thats not connecting anything but just adding material near the seam and then with that extra mass there you can get a puddle to jump the gap after its cooled off.. anywhere that will visually allow you to though overlap them instead of doing a butt joint itll be 5x easier

I love that Jon does not let good be the enemy of perfect.  Roll up your sleeves and give it a try.  Test out all your techniques and see which work and which don't.  Improve and iterate.  This is a great tutorial of how every-day guys can acquire new skills.  Great job!

kXa0vUy2Tlg.title: Designing Space Hardware is Hard
top_comments:
➡ I totally forgot to talk about Stress Corrosion Cracking, and insulators/charge buildup! So many constraints!

➡ What about a flexure hinge?
Yeah I totally forgot to mention this option, and even CAD'ed up a few designs. Ooops, sorry! 😅 The most common design is a curved spring steel flexure similar to a tape measure tape. There are a lot of variants to tune the opening force and stiffness. Really neat devices! The biggest disadvantage is that they are not rigid when in the stowed position (take a tape measure and bend it in half, it will flop around laterally a lot). They also need a fair amount of "dead space" when folded because you have to leave space for the tape loop.

That said they are very cool and a lot of groups have used them successfully!

➡ What about the torsion spring cold welding?
Still a concern! I believe missions will coat/lubricate their torsion springs just like the rest of the moving parts. My understanding is that it's slightly less of a concern though, because the spring isn't carrying the load of the panel. So under vibration it's just its own mass which makes it fairly resilient to galling/welding. The rounded profile will help reduce contact too

And my lapping shouldn't affect that profile much, a few passes with high grit paste will just knock off rough edges, not flatten it.
If it only ever needs to open once, maybe a flexure would be much simpler?

bdo3djJrw9o.title: How making a L.A.S.E.R. vector display crushed my soul
top_comments: Check out https://brilliant.org/bitluni/ for a 30 day free trial or a 20% discount for an annual subscription (sponsor)

I work with galvos for years... plastic 3D printed holder is absolute NO option. Motor should be placed in aluminium block with perfect thermal contact and block should be placed on heatsink. Some galvos are non insulated and their holder or heatsink must be electrically insulated from other potentials like a mains ground . Even 50°C decreases life of motor and cause irreversible changes in magnetic properties of core. This cheap motors cant be pushed for wide angle and even manufacturers data are on the edge. Drivers are tuned in safe zone for motors by manufacturer and if you turn pots and add more gain or adding more dumping factor for sharper edges means you can overloading motors very easily even on small angles. For better angle you need expensive motors with +/-30 degrees or try to find f/theta lens suitable for visible light which is hard to find - almost all of them are used in laser engravers which use infrared light. Fish eye lens for phone camera was surprising option.

i work with showlasers in my job and i might be able to give some insight.
the signal is +/-5V, since this is the ILDA standard. basically a d-sub connector on the back of any showlaser that connects the laser to the control system/interface.
that connection is basically analogue. it provides XY as +/-5V and 6 color signals of 0-5V.

the maximum angle of the galvo is low, since a bigger angle directly fights speed. showlasers are specified at 8° angle with their speed. if you want to increase one, you need to decrease the other. however there are lenses that expand the beam deflection if placed behind the galvo. maybe they will help. (as you tested)
also you got a very bad scanner(galvo) with 15kpps. even a very low end showlaser has 30kpps. a usable range is at 40 and the high end starts at 50kpps.
you might be able to snatch a used showlaser (or a broken one) for parts. you may look into old laserworld CS1000. if you are lucky, you may find one in the SE (speed edition) version. that one has a 50k scanner. those old CS MK1 are modular. so you will find the same scanner, laser diode drivers and so on.
The picture will be quite a bit better if you use a real 30 or 40kpps scanner.

i agree with you. you have overdriven your galvos quite a bit, resulting in the burned motor.
they are very delicate, require active cooling and careful adjustment. you can kill the motors even without messing with the driver. your scanning rate is important.
